Rating: 4
Yum. I wouldn't change a thing. To store chipotles, here's my secret: 99% of all recipes call for them minced or pureed, so when I open a fresh can I puree the whole thing in the blender, and put the leftover puree in a medium zipper freezer bag. I spread it out in the bag so it freezes in a thin layer, then break off whatever size piece I need.

Rating: 3
I made this dish for a dinner party of eight. The only adjustment I made was to add one more chicken breast and a cup of chicken stock to the sauce. There was plenty for everyone and it worked well to make the sauce early in the day and refrigerate it until an hour before showtime. Then I boiled the pasta, mixed in the sauce and popped it in the oven on 200 degrees until we were ready to eat when I added the final cheese and served. It was a hit and I was relaxed! I'd definately do it again.

Rating: 0
I write in response to the storing chipotles question (although the recipe looks great and is on the "to make" list). To preserve chipotles: place them individually on an aluminum pie plate (or something similar) and freeze them until solid. Then, transfer them to a freezer container. In this manner you can use them on an as needed basis.

